From: pi-stomp/JackBridge
Subject: netadapter: clear PI controller integrator on ringbuffer reset

JackAudioAdapterInterface::ResetRingBuffers() re-centers the slip-ring to
half-full and clears libsamplerate's filter state, but never touches the
PI controller's offset_integral. Across many ring failures the integral
accumulates without bound (Ki=1e-9, integration step = error in frames,
no anti-windup on the integral itself — only the output ratio is clamped
to [0.25, 4.0]). The accumulated windup biases the resample ratio further
off the true static factor with each cycle, which sails the ring toward
one wall, which triggers another failure sooner, which adds more error
to the integral. Net effect: failure rate ramps monotonically from
jackd start, end-to-end audio latency stays roughly constant (ring fill
position is decoupled from pipeline latency), and only a full netadapter
reload — which destroys and reconstructs JackPIControler — restores
clean operation.

JackPIControler::OurOfBounds() exists for precisely this purpose
(JackFilters.h:333) but has zero callsites in 1.9.22. Wire it up from
ResetRingBuffers().

--- a/common/JackAudioAdapterInterface.cpp
+++ b/common/JackAudioAdapterInterface.cpp
@@ -177,6 +177,11 @@
         for (int i = 0; i < fPlaybackChannels; i++) {
             fPlaybackRingBuffer[i]->Reset(fRingbufferCurSize);
         }
+        // pi-stomp: clear PI controller integrator windup. Upstream's
+        // OurOfBounds() exists for this but has no callers in 1.9.22,
+        // so the integral grows unbounded across resets and biases the
+        // ratio further off true on each cycle.
+        fPIControler.OurOfBounds();
     }

     void JackAudioAdapterInterface::Reset()
